Top of the line service at one of the best restaurants in SF. Reservations are made via phone/online 2 months prior to the date (Example- made on July 20 for Sept 20). Valet $11 Theres is a SET 5 course menu that is $117. OR the 3,4,5 Tasting Menu that is custom to you. Tasting Menu 3 course is $81, 4, is $99 and 5 is $117. These courses are flexible and you pick whatever you like-- it can be all 3 desserts, or 2 appetizers and 2 entrees, or all 5 appetizers. It doesnt have to be 1 appetizer, 1 entree, 1 dessert which I think is the best part about their tasting menus! Portion size is modified throughout the courses. Complimentary soup was given. It was a tasty red pepper soup topped with chives. I did the 5 course -Risotto -Foie Gras -Oysters w/caviar -Lemon Pepper Duck -Creme Brulee Sampler My boyfriend also had a 5 course -Seared Ahi -Oysters w/caviar -Scallops -Filet -Chocolate Souffle I could describe each item but there would be no point because every dish was great. Amazing texture and flavors. I do want to mention though, if you are celebrating a birthday they give you a complimentary chocolate cake. Without a celebration, they already give you a complimentary dish of little desserts. We ordered 1 dessert each as part of our 5 courses and we felt that at the end of the night we had way too much dessert especially since the portion of all 3 creme brulees was big considering it was a sampler. Next time, we would only order 1 dessert for us both and use the other course on food. A+ service as always in fine dining and food! Will always come back

Came here for dinner on a Saturday and we were so lucky they has space for us at the bar. The food is so amazing! We ordered the black caviar, shrimp ricotta, and thai soup. All were so yummy and filling. They gave us mini desserts afterwards which was too cute to eat.

Value: B+ $200/person is pretty steep, so expectations are high. Many months after this meal I do not remember a single dish. But I do remember the experience was solid. The service is what I would expect at this price range and the food was plentiful. There is a pre fixe option, but to try as many as we could we opted for 1 pre fixe and an assortment of other dishes. All of the food was good, some of it was GREAT! But I am not raving about Gary Danko to anyone. I left full and happy, but I think we can all find better value some place else.. just few places with the same level of service.

I still dream about the shiitake mushrooms with the seared tuna... the five course meal was absolutely amazing! I wish I could try everything! The ambiance was gorgeous and quiet, perfect for a romantic date. The service was great - I never felt rushed or watched with the flow of servings. I appreciated the quality of food, the selection and perfect suggestion of wine, and the beauty of the restaurant!

The only thing I wish I would have done differently is order my own bottle of wine instead of ordering the wine pairing. Other than that, my experience was flawless.

At the end of the night we were each given a small pumpkin muffin wrapped in beautiful gold wrap for breakfast.

The food that I ordered (foie gras, bass, bison, cheese, soufflé) was very tasty and deceptively filling. They even gave us a complimentary chocolate marquis cake with a candle to celebrate our 4 years together! Gary Danko was a great restaurant to have had an opportunity to eat in, but it was not a 5 star experience for me nor can I give the 4 star rating of "Yay! I'm a fan." I wanted to try a Michelin star restaurant during our trip in San Francisco. I've had one positive Michelin experience in Vienna, so I was hopeful that this restaurant would be similar to or even exceed my expectations. The food was okay. I liked that there was a large variety of appetizers, entrees, and desserts to choose from. You also have an option to pick a 3 course, 4 course or 5 course meal, and pick whatever dish you want. You are not limited to one appetizer, one main dish and one dessert, so you could have all main dishes if you want. I tried Risotto with Rock Shrimp, Seared Ahi Tuna, Branzini, Seared Sea Scallop, Coconut Thai Curry, and Roasted Quail. They were tasty, and some dishes such as Seared Ahi Tuna and Coconut Thai Curry were nicely presented, but they were not amazing nor creative as one may expect from a Michelin star restaurant. Some dishes were too salty for me. I liked the risotto the most. They gave us a small complimentary dessert tray, but I only tried a little bite. We also got complimentary pineapple cakes to take home. I'd say the dining experience in terms of service was similar to any high-end restaurant in the Greater Toronto Area (GTA). The wait staff offered to take our coats. They folded our napkins if we left our seats during the meal. They gave us complimentary bread and refilled it (We didn't want it but the waiter gave us more anyway). They were courteous and professional. In terms of food, I'd say that it was okay, and that there are better high-end restaurants, which offer unique and tasty dishes in the GTA.

My daughter and son-in-law ate here earlier this week, and my daughter got food poisoning. They called the restaurant back the next day to let them know, and the staff was very apathetic, and were convinced that her illness "certainly could not have come from their food!" Well it did, and was quite disappointing to have spent that much money on a meal that made you sick, but even worse to have a completely uncaring response!!

I literally don't know how to start this review because I was so ecsatic with my experience and the food here!!! My boyfriend took me to Gary Danko for our 3-year anniversary (lucky me!). He made our dinner reservation 2 months in advance and we were set! We chose the 4-course menu instead of the 5-course because we figured 4 courses was enough food already... And we chose 4 courses over 3 courses because 3 is too little to try at your first time at GD! :P Beware of a loooong review coming up... We shared: - Seared foie gras with caramelized onions and apples: Absolutely amazing! My first time having foie... I know, i've been missing out! I thought it would be too rich for me, but it was perfect. Because it was seared, it melted in my mouth! - Roasted butternut squash soup with duck confit ravioli and toasted hazelnuts: Strong squash flavor! I didn't get to try the ravioli (bf ordered this) but he enjoyed it! - Risotto with rock shrimp, dungeness crab, pumpkin, shimeji mushrooms and sage: Loved this! Probably one of the most popular things to order at GD. I've never had rissotto before (deprived?? maybe), but my first experience will be hard to beat! It was so creamy and flavorful, with big chunks of seafood too! - Glazed oysters with Osetra caviar, zucchini pearls and lettuce cream: A must order!! It was very seafood-y so definitely order it if you are a seafood lover like me. The oysters were creamy and sweet, and complemented the salty caviar. I ended up dipping my bread in the sauce after I finished! So good. - Roast Maine lobster with potato puree, mushrooms, edamame and tarragon: The lobster was incredibly buttery and so tender! I also loved the potato puree, much softer than mashed potatoes! I wanted to lick my plate after this dish. (did I? no....) The crunchy edamame and mushrooms added a nice texture as well. - Pan seared scallops with cannellini bean puree, garlic confit, tomato and basil: By far, my favorite entree! The scallops were perfectly seared with a crunchy outside and a buttery soft inside. I was blown away when I had my first piece. The garlic confit was the perfect addition. - Seared filet of beef with potato gnocchi, olive oil, swiss chard and stilton butter: I loved the beef but the real star here was the potato gnocchi... It was pillowy soft and delicious. You really must try it for yourself. Compared to what I thought gnocchi tasted like (*cough* Olive Garden soup *cough*), this blew me out of the water!! Oh yeah, and the beef was amazing too! I ate a large portion of this because my bf couldn't finish. It had the perfect outer crust while maintaining a medium rare inside. - Herb crusted loin of lamb with farrotto, dates, carrots and green chemoula: The presentation on the lamb was very nice! It was cut in slices so you could see the perfect cook on the meat. The lamb wasn't gamey at all either! We also got a complimentary anniversary dessert which was a chocolate mousse! Something very creamy and decadent to finish off our meal! They also came out with a tray of dessert samplers, which were more than enough to satisfy our sweet tooths afterwards! Service was phenomenal, and all the waiters and waitresses check up on you politely (but not in the annoying, come-by-when-you're-chewing sort of way) to ask how everything is. Napkins are folded when you leave your seat. Bathroom doors are opened for you. Tables are slid out so you can get back in your seat easily. Waters are filled even when they're 5/6 full already. Bread is constantly being refilled. People are always smiling. It's truly an amazing experience! I don't expect to be back anytime soon, but I hope (with all my heart) to be back eventually!

Loved it! I came to celebrate a friend's birthday and everything I ordered was solid. The ambiance, service and food were perfection. Our party of 9 enjoyed the private dining room that night. 3 courses: - Foie Gras: Since I ordered a dish from each section (appetizer, meat, dessert), my foie gras was generously sized. I enjoyed every bite of this! - Seared Filet of Beef: It was cooked nicely but didn't blow my mind. Wish I had gone with the duck or lamb. - Cheesecake: Delicious! I probably wouldn't have ordered this though had I known about the complimentary assorted mini-desserts. Conclusion: Highly recommend! I loved my experience here and can't wait to try the rest of the menu.

Took my wife to GD last night. Been here plenty of times. Why do I keep going back? One, flexibility. How many fine dining restaurants lets you pick and choose from the menu? Not many. I'm not a fan of sweets. I avoid it as much as I can. I ordered a five course: one app, two seafoods, and two lands. Pretty amazing. Second, food is simple. Presentation is great, ingredients are simple. I can relate to it and identify. I've been to 3 Michelin star restaurants. I can tell you this.. I don't remember what the heck I ordered. I don't remember what the presentation looks like nor do I care. Third, value at GD is great. I don't think paying $250+ per person for fine dining is worth it anymore. Its just a bit too much to spend let alone on food. I might as well buy my wife a new Chanel hand bag that will last awhile. Shhhh, don't tell her I said this. I read reviews and especially bad ones. I find it to be entertaining. People are angry because food is too simple, and they are too hungry. One of the challenges at GD is picking the right dish on the menu. You need to go out of your comfort zone. Do Avoid the salad, seared scallops, foie gras or sea bass, and the beef or pork tenderloin. You can get that anywhere. Try something you've never tried before like salmon with horseradish (first for me). Try a protein you don't see on the menu too often like the duck, quail or the bison. Wonderfully cooked and well plated. If you're going to order the Salad and complain about it, thats on you. Make the chef work for you - not the other way around. Again, GD is simple. Great flexility, and value. Great meal.

Best dinning experience EVER! The first thing that stands out right away is the customer service. From the moment you walk in, there is a hospitality from ALL the service staff. Overall Incredible experience. Gary Danko is exceptional all around. You get what you pay for and even more which is always great for a dinning experience and making you want to return. Took my friend here for his birthday dinner while we were in town visiting. Not that it's a huge deal, but the little things matter and he definitely lessened the experience. We chose the 5 course tasting menu. So we walked out of there with about. 660 bill. Don't think it was worth it, although they were certainly Generous with the portions.

I've dined at Danko a few times and each time, the food and service were consistent. The atmosphere at Danko isn't stuffy or pretentious (compared to say, Michael Mina, where the food was bland and the waiters were way too serious). If you're looking for a place to dine for a special bday or event or just simply beautifully crafted food to treat your palette and can't decide where to go from all the great offerings in SF, Danko will not disappoint!

    I literally don't know how to start this review because I was so ecsatic with my experience and the food here!!! My boyfriend took me to Gary Danko for our 3-year anniversary (lucky me!). He made our dinner reservation 2 months in advance and we were set! We chose the 4-course menu instead of the 5-course because we figured 4 courses was enough food already... And we chose 4 courses over 3 courses because 3 is too little to try at your first time at GD! :P Beware of a loooong review coming up...

    We shared:
    - Seared foie gras with caramelized onions and apples: Absolutely amazing! My first time having foie... I know, i've been missing out! I thought it would be too rich for me, but it was perfect. Because it was seared, it melted in my mouth!
    - Roasted butternut squash soup with duck confit ravioli and toasted hazelnuts: Strong squash flavor! I didn't get to try the ravioli (bf ordered this) but he enjoyed it!
    - Risotto with rock shrimp, dungeness crab, pumpkin, shimeji mushrooms and sage: Loved this! Probably one of the most popular things to order at GD. I've never had rissotto before (deprived?? maybe), but my first experience will be hard to beat! It was so creamy and flavorful, with big chunks of seafood too!
    - Glazed oysters with Osetra caviar, zucchini pearls and lettuce cream: A must order!! It was very seafood-y so definitely order it if you are a seafood lover like me. The oysters were creamy and sweet, and complemented the salty caviar. I ended up dipping my bread in the sauce after I finished! So good.
    - Roast Maine lobster with potato puree, mushrooms, edamame and tarragon: The lobster was incredibly buttery and so tender! I also loved the potato puree, much softer than mashed potatoes! I wanted to lick my plate after this dish. (did I? no....) The crunchy edamame and mushrooms added a nice texture as well.
    - Pan seared scallops with cannellini bean puree, garlic confit, tomato and basil: By far, my favorite entree! The scallops were perfectly seared with a crunchy outside and a buttery soft inside. I was blown away when I had my first piece. The garlic confit was the perfect addition.
    - Seared filet of beef with potato gnocchi, olive oil, swiss chard and stilton butter: I loved the beef but the real star here was the potato gnocchi... It was pillowy soft and delicious. You really must try it for yourself. Compared to what I thought gnocchi tasted like (*cough* Olive Garden soup *cough*), this blew me out of the water!! Oh yeah, and the beef was amazing too! I ate a large portion of this because my bf couldn't finish. It had the perfect outer crust while maintaining a medium rare inside.
    - Herb crusted loin of lamb with farrotto, dates, carrots and green chemoula: The presentation on the lamb was very nice! It was cut in slices so you could see the perfect cook on the meat. The lamb wasn't gamey at all either!

    We also got a complimentary anniversary dessert which was a chocolate mousse! Something very creamy and decadent to finish off our meal! They also came out with a tray of dessert samplers, which were more than enough to satisfy our sweet tooths afterwards!

    Service was phenomenal, and all the waiters and waitresses check up on you politely (but not in the annoying, come-by-when-you're-chewing sort of way) to ask how everything is. Napkins are folded when you leave your seat. Bathroom doors are opened for you. Tables are slid out so you can get back in your seat easily. Waters are filled even when they're 5/6 full already. Bread is constantly being refilled. People are always smiling. It's truly an amazing experience! I don't expect to be back anytime soon, but I hope (with all my heart) to be back eventually!

    Updated review

    Took my wife to GD last night. Been here plenty of times. Why do I keep going back? One, flexibility.  How many fine dining restaurants lets you pick and choose from the menu? Not many. I'm not a fan of sweets. I avoid it as much as I can. I ordered a five course: one app, two seafoods, and two lands. Pretty amazing. Second, food is simple. Presentation is great, ingredients are simple. I can relate to it and identify. I've been to 3 Michelin star restaurants. I can tell you this.. I don't remember what the heck I ordered. I don't remember what the presentation looks like nor do I care. Third, value at GD is great. I don't think paying $250+ per person for fine dining is worth it anymore. Its just a bit too much to spend let alone on food. I might as well buy my wife a new Chanel hand bag that will last awhile. Shhhh, don't tell her I said this.

    I read reviews and especially bad ones. I find it to be entertaining. People are angry because food is too simple, and they are too hungry.

    One of the challenges at GD is picking the right dish on the menu. You need to go out of your comfort zone. Do Avoid the salad, seared scallops, foie gras or sea bass, and the beef or pork tenderloin. You can get that anywhere. Try something you've never tried before like salmon with horseradish (first for me). Try a protein you don't see on the menu too often like the duck, quail or the bison. Wonderfully cooked and well plated.

    If you're going to order the Salad and complain about it, thats on you. Make the chef work for you - not the other way around.

    Again, GD is simple. Great flexility, and value. Great meal.

    8/4/2014Previous review

    Gary Danko is like the mainstream of Fine Dining. It's simple, easy to identify the ingredients. Nothing too over the top or too complicated.

    The flexibility of the menu (which you don't see often in other fine dining restaurants) is a huge plus. There are 3, 4 and 5 courses to pick up. You can order 5 courses from the fish and seafood menu or even the dessert menu!

    Recommendations:

    - risotto with dungeness crab etc. I also sampled the glazed oysters, which was very fresh with the fancy and expensive cavier. But I'm no expert on cavier so there's no need to exaggerate.

    - Roast Main Lobster with potato puree was very delicious.

    - Pan Seared Bass with herb and nettle gnocchi was also fantastic

    - seared sea scallops with sweet pea puree (they give you only two scallops) was great but I preferred the roast main lobster and pan seared bass over seared sea scallops.

    I used to be a big fan of meat, but over the years, I appreciate the fish and seafood more because it's more technical and very light and delicious.

    I'm not a fan of sweets. But the table next to me had Souffle and it looked amazing.

    Enjoy and try a bit of everything!

    Best dinning experience EVER!

    The first thing that stands out right away is the customer service. From the moment you walk in, there is a hospitality from ALL the service staff. My favorite was making way for me to go to the bathroom. I felt like royalty or at least what I think royalty must feel like.

    The food and wine pairing is fantastic. Our waiter was sweet and excellent regarding making many recommendations, especially to my likes and dislikes. No judgment of my level of Wine knowledge.

    The food, well there was not one dish I didn't like from start to finish. It kept getting better and better as the courses went on. The fish selections (Pan Seared Bass and Crusted Salmon Medallion) were exceptional. The flavors were just incredible. It made me think I could eat only fish for the rest of my life, it was so delectable.

    Finally they NAILED it with the ending. Not only is the dessert amazing, although I thought the two sauces for the soufflé was overkill. I mean no need to drown the soufflé, it is already so good, in fact it doesn't even need the sauces although the effect is pretty cool. Oh and I got to say when as my preference on how much sauce. I also LOVED that they send you a complimentary and generous sweets tray. Which has all these great bite size desserts, each one so delish! If your stuffed, no problem they can wrapped them up for you to take home and enjoy a little later. They also give you a little breakfast treat for the next morning so your experience continues...WHAT?!?! These kinds of details make a restaurant not only stand out but really special.

    Overall Incredible experience. Gary Danko is exceptional all around. You get what you pay for and even more which is always  great for a dinning experience and making you want to return. I'm confused as to why this restaurant is not Michelin rated? I have been to other Michelin rated restaurants that do not compare to GD.

    Thanks!
